<h2>In-class Lab 15.2</h2>
<ol type="I">
<li class="row0">
<p>Exercise 1</p>
<ol type="1">
<li class="row1">
<p>
If using your Linux VM, create directory <b>lab15</b> under your
<b>/var/www/labs</b> directory, if it does not exist.
Otherwise create directory <b>lab15</b> under
the document root of whatever web server you are using. On the MATC Windows lab
computers that will be: <b>C:\xampp\htdocs</b>
</p>
</li>
<li class="row0">
<p>
Open a text editor and create a PHP script named <b>lab15x2.php</b> . In this lab
you will send an email message to your instructor's email address.
</p>
</li>
<li class="row1">
<p>
Write the code to prepare and send an email using the PHP <b>mail()</b>
function. Your instructor will provide you with an email address to send the
message to.
</p>
</li>
<li class="row0">
<p>
Include your name in the subject line of the message so it will be easy for
the instructor to tell it's from you. Use a subject line similar to:
</p>
<blockquote><code>
$subject = 'PHP mail message from John Johnson'<br>
</code></blockquote>
</li>
<li class="row0">
<p>
Be sure to test the value returned by the <b>mail()</b> function, as we did
in lecture. Display either a success or failure message. Note that the mail()
function will not display anything if it executes successfully.
</p>
</li>
<li class="row1">
<p>
Note that if you are using Windows, your <b>php.ini</b> file must be modified
to contain a valid SMTP server such as: <code>mail.matcmadison.edu</code> 
in order to send mail.
</p>
<p>
If you are using your Ubuntu VM, you will need to install <b>sendmail</b>
using the Synaptic Package Manager in order to send mail messages.
</p>
</li>
<li class="row0">
<p>
After successfully sending a simple text email, try modifying your code to
send an HTML email message using the MIME format. Use the <b>mimemail.php</b>
example from Unit 15 as an example of how to do this.
</p>
</li>
<li class="row1">
<p>
Show your code to your instructor. We may not be able to get your PHP environment
properly set up to deliver the email to your instructor, but you can still get
full credit for this lab if your script successfully "sends" the email message
as indicated by the return code from the <b>mail()</b> function!
</p>
</li>
</ol>
<p><hr width="75%" /></p>
</li>
</ol>
